    "collapsible_row_list": {
      "type": "collapsible-row-list",
      "blocks": {
        "item-1": {
          "type": "item",
          "settings": {
            "expand_by_default": false,
            "icon": "leaf",
            "title": "Moonstone",
            "text": "<p>That floating blue glow — adularescence — comes from microscopic layers formed when ancient magma cooled millions of years ago. Two intermixed feldspar species separated at the molecular level, creating lamellae that scatter light through Rayleigh scattering — the same physics that makes the sky blue.</p><p>We cut every moonstone as a cabochon. The smooth dome focuses scattered light into a single luminous band. A faceted moonstone would destroy the glow. It's the antithesis of a diamond: soft, mysterious, unpredictable. A stone that shifts and breathes.</p>"
          }
        },
        "item-2": {
          "type": "item",
          "settings": {
            "expand_by_default": false,
            "icon": "t-shirt",
            "title": "Aquamarine",
            "text": "<p>The name literally means \"water of the sea.\" Iron traces in beryl crystal create the blue-green that Roman fishermen once carried as a talisman for safe voyages. The natural blue-green is increasingly valued by designers who appreciate its connection to actual ocean color, which is never pure blue.</p><p>We cut our aquamarine as cabochons — unconventional, but deliberate. Where a faceted aquamarine looks like ice, a cabochon looks like the sea: a deep, still pool of color, glowing rather than glinting. The smooth dome integrates seamlessly with flowing gold forms.</p>"
          }
        },
        "item-3": {
          "type": "item",
          "settings": {
            "expand_by_default": false,
            "icon": "package-open",
            "title": "African Tourmaline",
            "text": "<p>Tourmaline occurs in more colors than any other gemstone — its crystal structure can incorporate nearly every element on the periodic table. Our tourmalines come from artisanal mines in Mozambique and Tanzania, where miners work family-owned claims with hand tools, not industrial operations.</p><p>Mozambican copper-bearing tourmalines glow with an almost internal neon light. Tanzanian chrome tourmalines produce an electric green colored by the same elements as emerald. We choose African sources for the extraordinary color saturation and the traceable, transparent supply chain.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
